'19:21': [
{sup:"1a", word:"purposed", vrefs:"Rom. 1:13", lines:["The purpose was to carry out Paul&rsquo;s loving concern for the need of the poor saints in Jerusalem. At that time Paul was in Ephesus on his third ministry journey, busy with a heavy burden to carry out his ministry in Asia ({1Co16:8|1&nbsp;Cor. 16:8}-{1Co16:9|9}) and in Macedonia and Achaia ({1Co16:5|1&nbsp;Cor. 16:5}-{1Co16:7|7}; {Act20:1|Acts 20:1}-{Act20:3|3}). Nonetheless, he still had a burden to spare part of his time for the needy saints in Jerusalem. When he arrived in Corinth, he wrote his Epistle to the saints in Rome, expressing the purpose of his trip and begging them to pray for him concerning this purpose ({Rom15:25|Rom. 15:25}-{Rom15:31|31}). Although he was an apostle set apart by God for the Gentiles ({Act22:21|22:21}; {Gal2:8|Gal. 2:8}), Paul was still concerned for the Lord&rsquo;s interest among the Jews. His primary concern was for the Body of Christ universally, not merely for his part of the New Testament ministry among the Gentiles.","Besides this, his purpose in going to Jerusalem at this juncture might also have been to fellowship with James and the other apostles and elders in Jerusalem regarding the Judaic influence on the church there. According to Paul&rsquo;s teachings in the Epistles to the Galatians and the Romans, the decision made by the conference of the apostles and elders in {Act15|ch. 15} to resolve the problem concerning circumcision must not have been fully satisfactory to him. This undoubtedly troubled him because of his concern for God&rsquo;s New Testament economy, which is to build up the Body of Christ. James&rsquo;s word in {Act21:20|21:20}-{Act21:22|22}, after Paul had arrived in Jerusalem ({Act21:17|21:17}-{Act21:18|18}), and his proposal that Paul participate in the four Jewish believers&rsquo; Nazarite vow ({Act21:23|21:23}-{Act21:24|24}) seem to confirm this view."]},
{sup:2, word:"spirit", lines:["Since the Lord the Spirit dwelt in Paul&rsquo;s spirit ({2Ti4:22|2&nbsp;Tim. 4:22}; {Rom8:10|Rom. 8:10}-{Rom8:11|11}), Paul must have purposed according to the leading of the Lord the Spirit. See {Act17:16^1|note 16<sup>1</sup>} in {Act17|ch. 17}."]},
{sup:"b", word:"Macedonia", vrefs:"Acts 20:1; Rom. 15:26; 1&nbsp;Cor. 16:5; 2&nbsp;Cor. 1:16; 8:1; 9:2"},
{sup:3, word:"go", lines:["Paul did go to Jerusalem ({Act21:17|21:17}), and he did see Rome ({Act28:14|28:14}, {Act28:16|16})."]},
{sup:"c", word:"Jerusalem", vrefs:"Acts 20:16, 22; Rom. 15:25; 1&nbsp;Cor. 16:3"},
{sup:"4d", word:"see", vrefs:"Rom. 1:13; 15:24, 28", lines:["This desire of Paul&rsquo;s was fulfilled by the Lord when He brought Paul to Rome through his appeal to Caesar ({Act23:11|23:11}; {Act25:11^1|note 11<sup>1</sup>} in {Act25|ch. 25})."]},
],
'19:22': [
{sup:"a", word:"served", vrefs:"Acts 13:5"},
{sup:"b", word:"Timothy", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Cor. 16:10; Acts 18:5; 20:4; Rom. 16:21; 2&nbsp;Cor. 1:1"},
{sup:1, word:"Erastus", lines:["A city treasurer of Corinth ({Rom16:23|Rom. 16:23}; cf. {2Ti4:20|2&nbsp;Tim. 4:20}), of high rank, who probably had been converted by Paul&rsquo;s preaching in Corinth (cf. {Act18:8|18:8}) and had become an attendant to Paul."]},
{sup:2, word:"stayed", lines:["It was at this time, in Ephesus, that the apostle wrote his first Epistle to the church in Corinth ({1Co16:3|1&nbsp;Cor. 16:3}-{1Co16:10|10}, {1Co16:19|19}, and {1Co16:8^1|note 8<sup>1</sup>}; {Act4:17|4:17}; cf. {Act19:20|Acts 19:20}-{Act19:23|23}, {Act19:8|8}-{Act19:10|10}, {Act19:17|17}; {Act20:1|20:1})."]},
],
